# XCTest measure runs 10 iterations — reset state per iteration

XCTest `measure { ... }` runs the block 10 times by default to compute timing statistics. Tests that insert N rows and then assert `count == N` after `measure` are silently broken — they'll actually see 10N rows, and the test will fail on the count assertion even if the "real" thing being measured works fine.

**Why:** April 2026 `testPerformanceWithManyNotes` was stacking 10,000 notes across iterations and failing at `XCTAssertEqual(manager.notes.count, 1000)`. Worse: each iteration's timing was 14x the previous because `SimpleSwiftDataManager.addNote` does `notes.insert(note, at: 0)` — O(n) head-insertion into a growing Array — so iteration 10 took 20s vs iteration 1's 1.5s. Relative stddev was 56%. The fix was one line: `try? manager.clearAllData()` at the top of the measure block.

**How to apply:** Any `measure` block that mutates state must start with a reset step — clear the store, empty the directory, reset the counter, whatever the test is exercising. Put the reset inside the block, not before it. If you can't reset cheaply, move the state creation out of `measure` and only measure the pure hot path.

Secondary lesson: head-insertion into a growing Array (`array.insert(x, at: 0)`) is O(n). If a performance test is seeing wall-clock regression across iterations even with correct reset, that's a real signal — go profile the hot path.
